{"page_content": "def uniform_pdf(x: float) -> float: \n    return 1 if 0 <= x < 1 else 0\nThe probability that a random variable following that distribution is\nbetween 0.2 and 0.3 is 1/10, as you\u2019d expect. Python\u2019s random.random is a\n(pseudo)random variable with a uniform density.\nWe will often be more interested in the cumulative distribution function\n(CDF), which gives the probability that a random variable is less than or\nequal to a certain value. It\u2019s not hard to create the CDF for the uniform\ndistribution (Figure 6-1):\ndef uniform_cdf(x: float) -> float: \n    \"\"\"Returns the probability that a uniform random variable is <= x\"\"\" \n    if x < 0:   return 0    # uniform random is never less than 0 \n    elif x < 1: return x    # e.g. P(X <= 0.4) = 0.4 \n    else:       return 1    # uniform random is always less than 1", "metadata": {"producer": "calibre (4.6.0) [http://calibre-ebook.com]", "creator": "calibre (4.6.0) [http://calibre-ebook.com]", "creationdate": "2020-01-31T21:58:22+00:00", "source": "D:\\Users\\wpoga\\Documents\\Ebooks\\Antigravity Library\\Data Science from Scratch First Principles with Python by Joel Grus.pdf", "file_path": "D:\\Users\\wpoga\\Documents\\Ebooks\\Antigravity Library\\Data Science from Scratch First Principles with Python by Joel Grus.pdf", "total_pages": 513, "format": "PDF 1.4", "title": "Data Science from Scratch: First Principles with Python", "author": "Joel Grus", "subject": "", "keywords": "", "moddate": "2020-02-01T00:59:10+03:00", "trapped": "", "modDate": "D:20200201005910+03'00'", "creationDate": "D:20200131215822+00'00'", "page": 113}, "type": "Document"}
